  "11:44:32",assistant,text,"Oh, I can see it in your screenshot — the bubble balloons up over my whole face on a long sentence. That's a real problem and a good fix to make. Let me say back what I heard so we're aligned, then go read my own rendering code before I promise specifics.\n\n**What you're describing is actually two different split mechanisms:**\n1. **Display-only chunking** (voice stays one utterance): a sentence over some character threshold gets its *bubble text* split into chunks, and the bubble advances chunk-by-chunk **in sync with the audio playback** (timed by syllables, since speech duration tracks syllables better than characters). The voice is unbroken; only the *caption* pages through.\n2. **Real voice split** (voice + text both split): a comma wrapping a clause of several words becomes a **mini-sentence** — its own TTS utterance *and* its own bubble.\n\nPlus the easy win: **more top padding** so the bubble sits higher off my face.\n\nOne architecture note up front, so we scope it right: the **bubble display + padding** live in the **renderer** (live2d) — that's where I'll start, like you asked. But the **comma-as-mini-sentence voice split** lives **server-side** in the speak pipeline (it changes what TTS generates), and it's renderer-agnostic. So #1 and the padding are live2d work; #2 is a separate server change. Let me confirm that against the actual code.\n\nReading my rendering code now —"
