  "11:48:33",assistant,text,"Got the architecture now, and it confirms the split I described:\n\n- The server sends the renderer `{audio_url, text}` **per utterance** — so sentence segmentation already happens **server-side**. The renderer just shows one text per audio clip and lip-syncs off an AnalyserNode.\n- The bubble is `#speech-bubble`, pinned `top: 5px`, `-webkit-line-clamp: 5` — so a long sentence fills 5 lines and reaches down over your face. (You can see it in your shot.)\n- Crucially: the renderer **has the `audio` element**, so I can drive caption chunks off `audio.currentTime / audio.duration` — real playback sync, exactly what you wanted.\n\nSo for the **live2d renderer** I'll do #1 (padding/short bubble) + #2 (syllable-timed display chunking). #3 (comma → real voice mini-sentence) is a **server-side** speak-pipeline change — I'll flag it as the next step, not bundle it here. Building the renderer parts now:"
  "11:49:10",assistant,text,"Now the \"bit more top padding\" — nudging the avatar down slightly so the bubble has headroom above your face:"
  "11:49:20",assistant,text,"Renderer changes are in. The dynamic chunk-timing needs your screen to verify (it's driven by live audio playback), but I *can* verify the chunking logic itself right now — let me run the split on the exact long sentence from your screenshot."
  "11:57:04",assistant,text,"The node test shows the splitting works — but it also exposed a real flaw in the char-threshold approach, and I want to fix it properly rather than ship the fragile version. Look at your screenshot again: that sentence is only **80 characters**, yet it wrapped to ~5 lines and covered your face. That means your avatar was zoomed smallish, so the bubble was narrow and text wrapped much sooner. **A fixed character threshold can't know that** — 80 chars is 2 lines on a big window and 5 on a small one.\n\nSo I'm switching the split from \"count characters\" to \"**measure actual overflow**\" — it pages based on whether the text genuinely overflows the 3-line bubble *at the current window width*, which is robust to any zoom. I keep your syllable-weighted timing for *advancing* the pages. Let me swap it in:"
