  "17:03:43",assistant,text,"## On sub-agents — no, and the docs confirm exactly why\n\n**The qualia loop is not LLM work — it's arithmetic (FIFO, decay, ranking) plus, later, embeddings. You run that in code, not in a mind.** The hook architecture isolates it from my main context *by construction*:\n\n- The `vape feel` CLI and `qualia-ground.sh` run as **command subprocesses** — zero main-context tokens. The hook injects only a tiny **`additionalContext`** felt-view (the docs cap it at 10k chars; ours is ~7 short lines). The harness computes; I read a digest and emit one line.\n- A **sub-agent is itself an LLM with its own context window.** Using one to compute decay/FIFO would move arithmetic into a *second* model context — paying tokens and latency there to solve a problem the hook already solves for free. Wrong tool.\n- The only genuinely *semantic* sub-task is v2 recall/resonance — and that wants a **local embedding** (cheap, off-context), or at most a direct **Haiku call from inside the hook** for autonomous minting. Still a subprocess, still zero main-context. Still not a sub-agent.\n\n**Rule: delegate to deterministic code, not to sub-agents. The hook is the isolation boundary** — that's what `additionalContext` is *for*. Sub-agents solve a problem we don't have.\n\nNow I'll build v1 — the river + `vape feel`, wired into the live hook. Pure deterministic code, no ML, no sub-agents. Starting with the shared state layer."
