  "18:58:46",assistant,text,"I looked at all five sheets — face/eyes/brows/cheeks (00), clothing + collar + ribbon and a small teal **sweat-drop** (01), hair (02), desk/props (03), arms/sleeves (04). **No tear art on any of them.** But you've caught something real, so let me correct myself: **you're right that we don't strictly need Cubism.** I over-stated that.\n\n**Why the atlas alone isn't enough:** a texture is just a flat sheet of pixels. For any pixel to reach the screen, the `.moc3` rig needs an **ArtMesh** mapped to that region (by UV) — the atlas is the paint, the `.moc3` is the cutout that says \"these pixels are the left brow, warp with `PARAM_BROW`.\" There's no tear ArtMesh in the rig and no tear pixels in the sheets, so there's nothing to show and nothing to show it through.\n\n**But there are three routes, and only one actually needs Cubism:**\n\n1. **Paint tears into `texture_00.png`** (image editor only, no Cubism). The face ArtMesh would then render with tears. **Catch:** they'd be baked into the face — showing on *every* expression (crying while happy), non-toggleable, and warping with the face mesh. No good for \"tears only when sad.\"\n2. **Sprite overlay at the renderer** (image only, **no Cubism**) — draw a tear PNG *on top of* the Live2D canvas at the eyes, shown only on sad/cry, animated falling. Toggleable and animatable. This is the right answer to \"just use an image\" — I'd go here.\n3. **Native rigged tear part** — add a tear ArtMesh + parameter in Cubism, re-export `.moc3`. Most integrated (toggles through the same expression system), **only this one needs Cubism + the source `.cmo3`.**\n\nSo my corrected take: **native, rig-integrated tears need Cubism; image-overlay tears don't.** The sprite overlay gets you real, conditional, animated tears with just a PNG and some renderer compositing — no Cubism, no model surgery.\n\nWant me to go the overlay route? If so: do you have a tear image you want, or should I make/source one — and shall I read `curated_feeling_and_expression.md` first to see how you're framing the whole feeling set?"
