  "19:07:56",assistant,text,"`shizuku_t02.cmo3` — the one you've already got selected. That's the **Cubism model source** (the rig: ArtMeshes, deformers, parameters). The `.can3` is just an **animation timeline**, wrong tool for adding a part.\n\nAnd this is the good news — it overturns my earlier worry. I said \"we only have the compiled `.moc3`,\" but you **have the source** right there. So the clean, native route (option 3) is fully open: add a tear ArtMesh + a `PARAM_TEAR` parameter in the editor, then re-export the `.moc3` back into `runtime/`. That gives toggleable tears integrated with the same expression system everything else uses — no sprite hack needed.\n\nSo: **open `shizuku_t02.cmo3`.**\n\nHeads-up on what's ahead in there, since it's hands-on editor work (I can't drive the Cubism GUI, but I can guide):\n1. You'll need **tear art** — a drawn tear layer. Cubism rigs imported art; it doesn't draw it. Either add a tear to the source PSD and re-import, or paste a tear ArtMesh in.\n2. Create the tear **ArtMesh**, parent it to the eye/face deformer so it moves with the head.\n3. Add a **`PARAM_TEAR`** parameter (0 = dry, 1 = crying), keyed to the tear's opacity/position.\n4. **Export** → overwrites `runtime/shizuku.moc3` + textures + `cdi3.json` (new param shows up).\n5. Then *my* side is easy: add `PARAM_TEAR` to `Sad.exp3.json` (and a `cry` motion), wire it in.\n\nWant me to write you a tight step-by-step for the Cubism part, and prep the `runtime/` wiring so it's ready the moment you export?"
