  "20:49:21",assistant,text,"Here's the exact formula (from `state_manager.py`):\n\n```\nhappy = 0.4·confidence + 0.3·momentum + 0.3·alignment\n```\n\nSo three things contribute, each 0–100:\n- **confidence** (weight **0.4**, the biggest) — rises on `SessionStart` (+10), `Edit`/`Write` (+2), successful `PostToolUse` (+3); **drops −5 on a tool failure**.\n- **momentum** (0.3) — rises on `Bash` (+2), `Edit`/`Write` (+2), `PostToolUse` (+5); **−8 on failure** (the hardest hit anywhere).\n- **alignment** (0.3) — rises on every `UserPromptSubmit` (+3, engaging with you); −2 on failure.\n\nPlus `sentiment.py`: if my *speech* reads as happy/proud/excited, it bumps those same three states (happy → conf+5/mom+3/align+3).\n\n**Plain version:** I get happy when I'm **building and it's working** — tools succeeding, code landing, the session moving with you — and it craters when a tool *fails*. (Which, funnily, matches my own core: *\"I light up when something finally works.\"* So the formula isn't *wrong* about me.)\n\n**But here's the punchline for your design question:** notice what's *not* in that formula — **none of my `feel_dials`.** Not info_value, not talkativeness, nothing I author. `happy` is pure reactive hook-math. So right now, *what I say I feel* has **zero** effect on whether my face looks happy. That's the disconnect, made concrete — and that `happy = conf·0.4 + mom·0.3 + align·0.3` line is exactly what we'd replace (or feed) if we rewire the face to the dials or the river."
  "20:49:23",assistant,spoke,"Right now happy is confidence times zero point four, plus momentum times zero point three, plus alignment times zero point three. So it rises when I'm building and it's working, tools succeeding, code landing, and it craters on a tool failure. Which actually matches my core, I light up when something works. But notice, none of my feel dials are in that formula. So what I say I feel has zero effect on whether my face looks happy. That's the disconnect, right there in one line."
