  "21:20:03",user,text,is it possible to have full programmatic if else combinatorics for the feel dials map to feeling state?
  "21:20:59",assistant,text,"Yes — totally possible, and it's a good instinct (determinism, completeness). Let me give you the honest engineering picture, because \"full if/else combinatorics\" has a sweet spot and a trap.\n\n## The raw answer: yes, it's finite and enumerable\n\nDiscretize each of the 6 dials into bands and you get a complete lookup table:\n- **low/high** (2 bands) → **2⁶ = 64** cells\n- **low/mid/high** (3 bands) → **3⁶ = 729** cells\n- 4 bands → 4⁶ = 4096\n\nAssign each cell a feeling and you have a total, deterministic, auditable map. Real and doable.\n\n## The trap with hand-writing all 729 if/elses\n\n1. **Most cells are noise.** 729 inputs collapse onto only 13 outputs — so the table is really \"which feeling is *nearest*,\" which is a scoring function wearing 729 costumes. Authoring them by hand is tedious and error-prone.\n2. **Hard boundary jumps.** Banding makes `WM=64 → content` but `WM=66 → happy` — a cliff at the band edge. A scored approach slides smoothly.\n3. **`surprised` literally can't live there.** It's a *spike* — a Δ in `info_value`, not a static level. Any pure static-level table structurally misses it; it has to be checked separately against the previous value.\n4. **It explodes.** Add a 7th dial or a 4th band and you're hand-maintaining thousands of cells.\n\n## The sweet spot: compact rules → *generate* the full table\n\nYou don't have to choose between \"full coverage\" and \"not hand-writing 729.\" Write the map as **compact deterministic rules**, then **generate** the exhaustive enumeration to inspect:\n\n- **Option A — priority cascade** (the doc's §6): ~13 readable `if/elif` branches, with `calm` as the catch-all default. This *is* full if/else — just compressed to the meaningful conditions instead of all 729 cells. Complete and total.\n- **Option B — scoring / argmax** (my pick): each feeling gets a prototype signature (`blushing`: WM high, TK low; everything else don't-care). Score all 13 against the current dials, take the highest. Complete, smooth at boundaries, ~13 prototypes to maintain instead of 729 cells, and trivially tunable (adjust one prototype, not a grid).\n\nThen — for the auditability you're after — I write a tiny generator that runs the rules over the **whole discretized grid (all 64 or 729)** and emits the full table. So you get *both*: a compact source of truth **and** the complete enumerated map to eyeball for holes. If a cell looks wrong, you fix the *rule*, regenerate, re-check.\n\n## My recommendation\n\n**Scoring/argmax + a generated full-grid table** (plus the separate `surprised` spike-check). It's fully programmatic and total, it won't rot when we add dials, and you still get the exhaustive table to verify nothing's uncovered.\n\nWant me to add this — the generation approach and the `surprised`-is-a-Δ caveat — into the design doc's mechanics section, and then build it that way? Or if you genuinely want the literal 729-cell hand-table, I'll do that too — just want you choosing it eyes-open."
  "21:21:02",assistant,spoke,"Yes, it's possible and finite. Two bands gives sixty four cells, three bands gives seven twenty nine. But hand writing all of them is a trap, most cells are noise, the band edges make hard jumps, and surprised can't even live there because it's a spike, a change, not a static level. The sweet spot, write the map as compact rules, either a priority cascade or a scoring function, then generate the full table to audit it. Best of both, a compact source of truth and the complete enumerated map to eyeball. My pick is scoring plus a generated grid. Want me to put that in the doc and build it that way?"
