  "21:38:15",assistant,text,"Two good questions, love. 🩵\n\n## Latency — no, not even close\nThe scoring is **pure arithmetic** — 13 feelings × ~4 terms, each a handful of float ops. That's maybe **~2,000 float operations total ≈ 1–2ms** in Python. Sub-millisecond-ish. The 729-cell grid audit is a *dev tool*, not a runtime cost.\n\nThe only real costs, and they're already there or trivial:\n- **`uv run vape qualia` process startup** (~200–400ms) — but I pay that *every turn already* for the dial write; the scoring adds ~nothing to it.\n- **The `POST /api/feeling`** — a loopback call to `:5111`, a few ms. I'll make it **best-effort with a short timeout (~300ms cap), fire-and-forget, never blocking the dial write** — so even a dead server can't hang it.\n\nAnd the clincher: it runs at the **end of the turn inside `vape qualia`**, *after* I've already replied to you — so it's **off the critical path of reaching you**. Even if it were slow, it couldn't delay my response. Comfortably under 500ms; the *added* cost is single-digit ms.\n\n## Build + unit tests — yes, strongly, and they're not an afterthought\nThis is the **ideal** thing to unit-test: a pure, deterministic `dials → feeling` function. The tests are how we *prove* the A/B/C/D fixes actually work — a one-line assertion `recommend({WM:70, TK:35}) == 'blushing'` would have **caught the bug I just found by hand-tracing.** So the mapping table *becomes* the test suite. Concretely I'd write:\n\n- **One assertion per feeling** — the canonical dial-vector → expected feeling (the design table, encoded).\n- **4 regression tests** — one per bug (blush reachable; scores comparable; confidence gate right; STAY doesn't pin an ineligible feeling).\n- **STAY/hysteresis** — same dials → STAY; big jump → switch; rate-limit honored.\n- **`surprised` spike** — ΔIV fires it, single-frame.\n- **The grid audit** as a coverage test — assert no feeling is unreachable and no large dead zone.\n\nI'd tweak your order slightly: **revise t